  "doc_id": "40031",
  "text": "Light signals are received by the retinal cells which transmit the input to the SCN via the retino-hypothalamic tract. In the SCN, calcium influx occurs in response to the interaction of glutamate with NMDA (N-Methyl-D-aspartate) receptors, leading to the activation of IP3 (inositol triphosphate) and ryanodine receptors or acting directly on posttranscriptional mechanisms [CITATION_1] . Upon signal reception, the pacemaker generates and sustains rhythms that are subsequently diffused to the peripheral organs via output pathways such as the glucocorticoid pathway [CITATION_2] . Peripheral oscillators exist within the different tissues throughout the organism being present in most cells ( Fig. 1 ) and regulate various biochemical processes [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] .",
